            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <div type="textpart" n="1">
                <p>Ogham: 'of <foreign xml:lang="pgl">Gendilus</foreign>'</p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                        <p><q>GENDILI is a genitive of one or other of the attested Latin names <foreign xml:lang="la">Gentilius, Gentilis</foreign> or <foreign xml:lang="la">Gentillus</foreign>, with Ir. /nd/ substituted for the /nt/ that was lacking in Primitive Irish. A related borrowing in Welsh can be seen at Patrishow 1 (B43) in GENILLIN = MW <foreign>Gen(n)illyn, -in</foreign> and perhaps in the place name <foreign>Tref Ginhall</foreign> (var. <foreign>Gynnhill, Gynhil</foreign>) in the Book of Llandaf...</q> (Edwards 2007, 504).</p>
                        <p><q>Although the roman inscription is fragmentary, enough survives to suggest that it mirrored the ogam inscription, being simply a personal name in the genitive case, though the former existence of a longer one-line inscription is also possible</q> (Edwards 2007, 504).</p>
            </div>
